body:
Hi @beltekylevi, thanks for the issue!

This seems to be a bug in ignore v4.0.6:

```js
const ignore = require("ignore");

// logs `false` with ignore v4.0.6, `true` with ignore v5.2.0
console.log(
    ignore().add("src/\\[index\\].js").ignores("src/[index].js")
);

```

The bug was fixed in [v5.1.5](https://github.com/kaelzhang/node-ignore/releases/tag/5.1.5) ("fixes escaping for square brackets"), but `@eslint/eslintrc` still [uses v4.0.6](https://github.com/eslint/eslintrc/blob/9b719813fc6f023b722168a4f67d895106e875ce/package.json#L72).

We could update the dependency in `@eslint/eslintrc` to `"ignore": "^5.2.0"` and this issue would most likely be fixed (we would certainly add tests to confirm). Since ignore v5 has a breaking change, we should probably use it with `{ allowRelativePaths: true }` option to get the v4 behavior that eslintrc might be relying on, as we did in https://github.com/eslint/eslint/pull/15439 for eslint/eslint.

That update seems a bit risky though, and eslintrc will be replaced by the new config system in the next major release anyway. 

@nzakas what do you think, should we switch to ignore v5.2.0 in `@eslint/eslintrc` and see what happens?
